<HL>
   Pinnacle West to Use
   PacifiCorp Proceeds
   To Reduce Its Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PPW PNW
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Pinnacle West Capital Corp., after agreeing to
a power-swapping deal that ended efforts by PacifiCorp to
acquire the company, said it would use proceeds from the deal
to reduce debt.
   At a meeting with securities analysts, Pinnacle West said
it would add the proceeds to its $750 million debt-reduction
plan, increasing the plan to $970 million by the end of 1993.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts were surprised yesterday by the subdued reaction
of investors attending the meeting, many of whom saw Pinnacle
West stock plunge Tuesday to $12.375 a share from $16.125 as
arbitragers unloaded stock in large quantities. The stock
recovered, however, to $12.875 a share yesterday in another
day of heavy trading. Volume on the New York Stock Exchange
totaled 1.7 million shares yesterday and 2.2 million on
Tuesday compared with 130,000 on Friday before the
announcement of the pact.
   "People came out of the meeting with a feeling that while
there would be no instant gratification from a sale of
Pinnacle West, the company was doing the right things to
improve in the long run," said Barry Abramson, a utility
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. Last Friday,
Pinnacle West announced an agreement to swap electric power
on a seasonal basis with PacifiCorp, effectively ending
efforts by PacifiCorp to acquire Pinnacle West for $21 a
share, or $1.82 billion. PacifiCorp agreed to pay $220
million in cash for exchange of power from Arizona Public
Service Co., a Pinnacle West utility subsidiary.
   Yesterday, Pinnacle West Chairman Richard Snell praised
the pact, saying he was "absolutely convinced" that it was a
"heck of a deal." Mr. Snell said that with the addition of
$220 million, Pinnacle would be able to retire $970 million
in debt by the end of 1993. As result, Pinnacle West hopes to
raise the book value of the company to $20 a share compared
to $16.31 in 1989 and restore its common-stock dividend by
the end of 1993. The company suspended its quarterly payout
of 40 cents a share last October.
   After the meeting, Mr. Snell said in an interview that
PacifiCorp's $21-a-share offer was "substantially" below the
company's own assessment of its value. He wouldn't elaborate,
but some analysts said the difference was about $3 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Smoking Parents
   Risk Tots' Health,
   According to Study
   ----
   By Ron Winslow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<IN>
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
</IN>
<LP>
   Children exposed to heavy amounts of tobacco smoke at home
are more than twice as likely to develop lung cancer later in
life than those who grow up in smoke-free households, a new
study says.
   The finding adds to the growing body of evidence that
nonsmokers' health may be damaged by other people's smoke. It
is one of the first studies to find that parents who smoke
present a potential cancer risk to their children.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It may be particularly important to protect children and
adolescents from this environmental hazard," say the authors
of the report, published in today's edition of the New
England Journal of Medicine.
   But the report found no statistically significant link
between lung cancer among nonsmokers and spouses who smoke,
or environmental smoke from the workplace or social settings
such as restaurants -- a development a representative of the
tobacco industry considered encouraging.
   The report "is in agreement with what we've been saying
{about} environmental tobacco smoke in the workplace, the
home and social settings for adults," said Steve Parrish,
vice president, corporate scientific affairs, at Philip
Morris Cos., New York. He also played down the significance
of the conclusion about the impact on children, saying
several other studies didn't turn up any evidence of
increased cancer risk.
   Mr. Parrish said the report supports the industry's
position that there isn't any justification for banning use
of tobacco in the workplace.
   The study's findings were based on interviews with 191
nonsmokers recently diagnosed with lung cancer in 23 counties
in New York State as well as 191 nonsmoking control subjects,
matched by age, sex and county of residence.
   The researchers, led by Dwight T. Janerich, an
epidemiologist at the Yale University School of Medicine, New
Haven, Conn., focused on exposure to tobacco smoke in the
household, although they also queried participants about
workplace and social setting exposures.
   Why children would be vulnerable to cancer is a question
for further study, Dr. Janerich said, but he speculated that
their lungs could be more suspectible to damage from smoke
than those of adults or that a long latency period is
required for the cancer to develop. The average age of cancer
patients in the study was about 67. Dr. Janerich disputed
that the report undermined previous research showing a 38%
increased risk of lung cancer for nonsmokers living with
smoking spouses. He also said non-household data wasn't
sufficiently firm to reach definitive conclusions.
   The study estimated that 17% of lung cancer among
nonsmokers "can be attributed to high levels of exposure to
cigarette smoke" at home when they were under 21 years old.
The scientists defined high levels as at least 25
"smoker-years" of exposure -- a calculation based on the
number of years a person lived in a residence multiplied by
the number of people in the household who smoked.
   The researchers acknowledged that the findings could have
been affected by the differences in the ability of
participants to recall details of lifetime tobacco exposure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Help-Wanted Ads
   Stayed at Low Level
   In Survey for July
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Help-wanted advertising continued its sluggish
pace in July, unchanged from June's five-year low.
   The Conference Board said its index of help-wanted
advertising remained at 132 in July, sharply down from a
year-earlier 147. June's figure was revised from 133. The
index, a seasonally adjusted indicator of hiring plans, uses
1967 as a base of 100.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although July's lackluster results had been expected, the
Conference Board said a previously optimistic outlook for the
second half has been harmed by the risk of war in the Middle
East.
   "As of Aug. 1, the economy in general, and the labor
market in particular, was poised for a modest uptick in the
second half of this year," said Conference Board economist
Ken Goldstein. "However, events in the Middle East changed
all that." Iraq invaded Kuwait Aug. 2, leading to the current
armed standoff in the region between Iraq and U.S.-led forces
and a world-wide trade embargo against Iraq.
   Mr. Goldstein said exporters, business investors and
consumers are more likely to put some plans on hold because
of that crisis. As a result, no big staff expansions are
expected in the next few months, which could hurt chances of
quickly turning around help-wanted volume growth.
   Nevertheless, the independent business research group said
it doesn't expect the economy to head into a recession,
although growth will be sluggish.
   The worsening economic prospects could be harmful to the
New England and Middle Atlantic states, which seemed on the
verge of coming out of a steep decline. The New England
region posted a 2.5% increase in want-ad volume in July.
   Job advertising in the Mountain, East South Central and
Pacific regions started to decline at a faster pace in July,
the Conference Board said. The West South Central region
remained stable, however.
   The index is compiled from monthly surveys of advertising
volume in 51 major newspapers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0111
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0111.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Sooners, Better Late Than Never,
   Lift the Lid on Capitol Spending
   ----
   By Todd Mason
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   OKLAHOMA CITY -- They're raising the roof here, but
they're doing it by the book -- sort of.
   In a 1989 novel by Jim Lehrer, fictional Oklahoma Gov.
Buffalo Joe Haman -- Chip to his friends -- is tormented by
the sight of the statehouse's flat roof, a mocking reminder
that in 1916 his state ran out of money before it could build
a dome atop the capitol. He exhorts any crowd of two or more
citizens to "Crown Oklahoma," which happens to be the title
of the book by Mr. Lehrer, of public television's
McNeil/Lehrer News Hour.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Actually, Oklahomans did run out of money before finishing
the capitol building in 1916. After Oklahoma wildcatters
struck oil in the late 1920s, the state had the means to
complete the dome but lost interest. State residents were
content to boast of the only state capitol in the U.S. with
working oil wells on its grounds.
   Now, since the capitol wells and the state economy began
drying up in the mid-1980s, there is growing sentiment here
to raise the dome and, with it, state morale. So Gov. Henry
Bellmon and Capitol DOMERS Inc. (Dedicated Oklahomans
Marshaling Excellence and Rallying Spirits) have kicked off a
fund-raising campaign not only to crown the statehouse but
also to pave a piece of its lawn.
   The DOMERS group has its roots in the recession that has
gripped the state for much of the past decade. In 1987,
Oklahoma City activist Carol Gwin decided that finishing the
capitol building could lift the state's spirits. To get the
job done, she recruited other retirees, including Adm.
William J. Crowe, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff and currently a professor at the University of
Oklahoma.
   The nonprofit group hopes to raise $14 million for the
dome and to build a plaza at the south entrance of the
capitol building. To help raise the money, the group is
offering citizens the right -- for $250 each -- to have
paving stones for the plaza engraved with names of their
choosing. "This is a symbol of our efforts to move forward,"
says architect Paul B. Meyer, a consultant to the Capitol
Preservation Commission.
   After Mr. Lehrer's book appeared, members fell into a long
debate. Should they lift its title for the name of their
campaign? "We would have had to make it `Crown Oklahoma,
Crown Oklahoma,'" cracks Mr. Meyer, "because Buffalo Joe had
a habit of saying everything twice." Instead the group
settled for "Raising Oklahoma."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
