</DOCID>
<HL>
   Salomon Is Planning
   To Almost Dismantle
   Philipp Brothers Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   SB
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Salomon Inc. outlined plans that virtually
would dismantle its struggling Philipp Brothers unit.
   Salomon said it will fold parts of Philipp Brothers into
other subsidiaries as part of a "major downsizing and
repositioning" of the commodity unit, which has been
unprofitable for six consecutive quarters. Other Philipp
departments will be sold.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The announcement marks a full circle for Philipp Brothers:
Initially, it was part of Phibro Corp., which acquired
Salomon Brothers in 1981. Philipp Brothers has had a pretax
loss of $83 million so far this year, tarnishing what
otherwise have been impressive earnings at Salomon's
securities and energy segments.
   In a news release, Salomon said Philipp's precious-metal
trading group will be absorbed by its Salomon Brothers Inc.
securities unit. Fertilizers and countertrade departments
will be folded into Phibro Energy, Salomon's big oil trading
and refining subsidiary.
   Meantime, Salomon is negotiating to sell Philipp's
nonferrous-metal department, a group that includes trading in
copper, aluminum, nickel, tin and zinc. Salomon blamed this
year's first-quarter pretax loss of $62 million for Philipp
on unspecified trades in nonferrous metals.
   Cocoa trading will continue to be conducted within Philipp
Brothers, Salomon said, although cocoa operations will be at
Phibro Energy. Phillip Brothers has cut back sharply from the
approximately 150 commodities it traded at the time of the
Phibro-Salomon merger to a handful.
   Salomon has said it will take a pretax charge of as much
as $200 million, expected in this quarter, to shrink the
ailing unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0053
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0053.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rash of FAA Retirements
   Spurs Concern by Airlines
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<GV>
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The airline industry said that it is
concerned about a rash of retirements among key Federal
Aviation Administration personnel, including air traffic
controllers.
   The Air Transport Association, which represents major
carriers, said the agency's loss of 341 people last month
jeopardizes the FAA's critical air traffic control and
airways operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There are approximately 50,000 FAA employees.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar confirmed the figure and said it
was twice the normal number of retirees for a month. The
increase, he said, was primarily because of concern over
possible changes in federal retirement rules.
   Aviation Daily, which reports on the airline industry,
stated on Tuesday that the retirees included 117 controllers,
84 electronic technicians, 17 engineers, 11 safety
inspectors, two FAA pilots and 110 in other categories.
   The Bush administration, in congressional budget
negotiations, has proposed eliminating a provision that
allows employees to get back their individual retirement
contributions in two annual lump sums.
   If the rules change, only those who retired 30 days before
the program expires Sept. 30 would be eligible to get the
lump-sum payments.
   Mr. Farrar said controllers are eligible to retire at age
50 if they have worked for 20 years and at any age after 25
years of active air traffic control work.
   FAA employees contribute 7% of their pay to the retirement
program and can receive it all back in two payments at the
end of service, while continuing to receive a reduced monthly
payment based on government contributions to the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- G-III Apparel Group Ltd.:
   Per-Share Profit Estimate
   Is Below Previous Forecast
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GIII
</CO>
<IN>
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<LP>
   G-III Apparel Group Ltd., New York, said it expects to
post per-share earnings of $1.70 to $1.80 for the fiscal year
ended July 31.
   Although the maker of leather apparel said the estimate
would represent an increase of 30% to 40% from the
year-earlier's $1.28 a share, it would be below the range of
$1.85 to $1.95 it estimated last week. Average weighted
shares outstanding rose about 20% in fiscal 1990.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, G-III
Apparel's shares closed at $6.75, down 16%, or $1.25.
   Morris Goldfarb, president and chief executive officer,
said profitability was lower than expected because of
"pressures in the retailing environment" that affected the
company's profit margins. Officials added that the earlier
estimate was given before the company had all the figures.
   Mr. Goldfarb said the company was "encouraged" by sales so
far in the fiscal 1991 first quarter.
   The company also estimated sales for the year rose 64% to
about $162 million from $99 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
