</DOCID>
<HL>
   USX Hails Project
   In Dying Steel Town
   As a Return to Roots
   ---
   But the People of Braddock,
   Carnegie's First Mill Site,
   Do Not Expect a Rebirth
   ----
   By Dana Milbank
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B12
</SO>
<CO>
   X
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRADDOCK, Pa. -- USX Corp. will bring in bagpipers
tomorrow for the launch of a $250 million investment at its
historic steel mill here. But not everyone in this boarded-up
town is joining in the parade.
   The company says the investment -- in a continuous slab
caster by its USS steelmaking division -- ensures the
survival of steel in the industry's cradle, the depressed Mon
Valley region near Pittsburgh. The steel giant had considered
abandoning the region entirely during steel's skid in the
1980s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There aren't many steelworkers left in Braddock to
celebrate, though. In the past decade, USX reduced employees
in the area to 4,000 in three plants from 30,000 in five
plants as the company focused its activities more on
flat-rolled sheet steels for such customers as auto and
appliance makers. The union says the new caster will actually
cut employment by as much as 400, but the alternative --
shutting down -- was worse.
   For USX, the project is a nostalgic return to its roots:
The caster will be part of the Edgar Thomson plant, Andrew
Carnegie's first steel mill, and the bagpipers will recall
the steel mogul's Scottish heritage. The equipment the caster
will replace, vintage 1938, would have been more appropriate
to Mr. Carnegie's time.
   The dual-strand caster, which will be completed in
mid-1992, will have an annual capacity of 2.6 million tons.
Continuous casting eliminates several laborious and
energy-intensive steps in making flat-rolled steel,
significantly reducing processing time and lowering costs.
The state-of-the-art caster will also improve quality.
   Pittsburgh-based USX agreed to build the caster in a labor
agreement reached in 1987. It also plans a similar-size
investment to rebuild a nearby strip mill, which will use the
steel made in Braddock.
   "It's a recommitment to the Mon Valley," USS President
Thomas C. Graham says of the caster. But, he adds, "it
couldn't transform (the valley) back on the scale that it
once was."
   Braddock Mayor Thomas Napolitano isn't expecting any
miracles, either, though he says Braddock will take what it
can get. "When they put that kind of money in a town like
this, you know they're going to stay for a few years.
Hopefully, we'll get something back in this town."
   Braddock's population, which 25 years ago was about
20,000, is down to 4,600. When steel left town, so did the
movies, jewelry stores, even the grocery store. For a while,
the only work to be found was in boarding up or knocking down
buildings. Locals describe it as a giant parking lot with no
cars.
   Braddock folks "don't know what (the caster) is, but they
figure something new is coming in," said Paul Tkach, a
retired steelworker in Braddock.
   But nobody expects a return to prosperity for the Mon
Valley. "No way," said Mr. Tkach. "It'll never be that way
again."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900906-0034
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900906-0034.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S., Arco Chemical
   Settle Dispute on Deal
   With Union Carbide
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   ARC UK RCM TX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEWTOWN SQUARE, Pa. -- The Federal Trade Commission and
Arco Chemical Co. agreed to settle antitrust litigation over
the company's proposed $220 million acquisition of certain
assets of Union Carbide Corp.
   Under a provisional consent agreement, Arco Chemical,
which is 83%-owned by Atlantic Richfield Co., Los Angeles,
will divest itself of the propylene glycols business it
agreed to buy from Carbide, based in Danbury, Conn. Propylene
glycol is used in products including fiberglass, paints and
cosmetics.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Arco Chemical will retain a urethane polyols business to
be acquired from Carbide. But it will divest itself of a
so-called tolling arrangement whereby Texaco Chemical Co., a
unit of Texaco Inc., produces polyols that Arco Chemical then
sells. Urethane polyols are used in making polyurethane
cushions, among other things.
   Arco Chemical will waive provisions in previous agreements
under which Carbide and Texaco agreed not to compete in the
polyol and propylene glycol business. Arco Chemical also will
drop certain objections it had raised to a technology that
Texaco Chemical Co. has been developing to make propylene
oxide. Arco Chemical had questioned whether some of its own
technology was being used by Texaco Chemical, but a patent
infringement suit hadn't been filed. Texaco Chemical doesn't
yet make commercial quantities of propylene oxide.
   The propylene oxide market, whose derivatives end up in
many consumer products, wasn't directly involved in Arco
Chemical's agreement with Carbide. But the Carbide lines to
be acquired by Arco Chemical are big buyers of propylene
oxide, and Arco Chemical is a big producer. The Arco
Chemical-Carbide transaction would thus remove a buyer from
the market and, the FTC argued, act as a deterrent to new
sellers who would have competed for that business.
   Carbide will keep the full $220 million payment made by
Arco Chemical under terms of its original agreement with Arco
Chemical.
   Carbide and Arco Chemical each will pay $1 million to the
federal government as settlement of certain issues related to
the timeliness with which the companies filed information
about their transaction. The payment doesn't represent
admission of wrongdoing by either company.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Arco
Chemical rose 25 cents to $34, while Carbide fell 25 cents to
$16.125.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
