<HL>
   Ex-President of Unit
   Of Teledyne Pleads
   Guilty in Fraud Case
</HL>
<DATE>
09/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TDY
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- The former president of a Teledyne
Inc. division pleaded guilty to one count of making false
statements to the Defense Department in connection with an
alleged scheme to defraud the Navy on a helicopter contract.
   The ex-president of Teledyne Hydra-Power, 69-year-old
Cirino Giampapa of Massapequa, N.Y., entered the plea in U.S.
District Court here. Also, Morton Baine, 54, of New Rochelle,
N.Y., a former Teledyne Hydra-Power controller, pleaded
guilty to conspiring with others at the division to defraud
the U.S. and to submit false claims to the Defense
Department.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Attorney's office in Manhattan said the alleged
scheme involved the submission of fraudulent labor-hour
figures to inflate the prices Teledyne Hydra-Power charged
for parts. The government said the false claims totaled more
than $4.5 million.
   Teledyne Hydra-Power is a division of Los Angeles-based
Teledyne Inc., which has diverse manufacturing interests. In
November, Teledyne Inc. agreed to pay the U.S. $11.9 million
to cover the overcharges and penalties.
   Mr. Giampapa, who will be sentenced Nov. 14, faces a
possible fine of as much as $10,000 and a maximum prison
sentence of five years. Mr. Baine, whose sentencing is
scheduled for Nov. 8, faces a fine of as much as $250,000 and
five years in prison.
   Carl Bernstein, attorney for Mr. Baine, declined comment.
Walter Bonner, Mr. Giampapa's attorney, couldn't be reached.
</TEXT>
